The paper deals with supervised learning with random decision trees, which is a topic that falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses differentially-private versions of the algorithm, which involves privacy-preserving techniques, and thus falls under the category of cryptography and security (cs.CR). The analysis of the algorithm involves mathematical proofs and upper-bounds, which suggests that the paper could also belong to the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the accuracy of the algorithm and its dependence on the number of random decision trees, which suggests that it could belong to the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the paper proposes differentially-private versions of the algorithm, which involves information theory and privacy-preserving techniques, and thus could also belong to the category of information theory (cs.IT).
